[1
Date: Mon, 20 Sep 1999 10:50:46
From: Matt <mtaylor@cadvision.com>

In your comments regarding Bluetongue you suggested that it occurred
'throughout the US and Canada'.
To the best of my knowledge, CanadaÂ´s only Bluetongue occurrences have been
confined to the Okanagan Valley, B.C. There are movement control
restrictions for livestock out of this area. There have been some imported
instances of Bluetongue, as with other countries, but these have been traced
back to US imports believed to have been infected at time of importation.
The generally accepted position on Bluetongue in Canada is that there is no
competent vector, outside the Okanagan Valley.
Even inside the Okanagan Valley, occurrences of Bluetongue are rare. Last
summer there was an outbreak, with 2 animals confirmed as positive. The
outbreak before that was several years ago. Sentinel animals are in place.
There are movement controls, as noted above.
Canada is recognized internationally as being Bluetongue-free except for the
Okanagan Valley. This confers a number of trade benefits in the
international market place, for our cattle and sheep based industries. The
distinction results in preferential access to some markets, and access of
any sort to some others.
Suggest you may want to confirm the above with the Canadian Food Inspection
Agency. You can do so via Dr. Claude Lavigne, Deputy Director, Animal
Health & Production Division (clavigne@em.agr.ca). We don't need trading
partners getting the idea that we're not free.
---
Matt
mtaylor@cadvision.com
[In the ProMED posting Epizootic hem. disease, deer - USA (New Jersey) (02)
990913234621, the wording of the statement is in error. I offer my
apologies. The statement should have read that bluetongue has occurred in
one very limited area of Canada and throughout the US. - Mod.TG
