[3
Date: Fri, 01 Oct 1999 09:50:53 -0400
From: "John Kellar" <jkellar@EM.AGR.CA>

The moderator in comments alluded to the distribution of Epizootic
Hemorrhagic Disease (EHD) and Bluetongue within Canada. In response to the
misinformation conveyed, I would note Bluetongue and EHD have been the
subject of continuous surveillance throughout Canada for 25 years, since
Bluetongue was first detected in its only recognized periodic focus, the
lower Okanagan Valley of British Columbia.
Cattle, the vector's preferred host, are tested serologically at slaughter
every 3 years, with systematic random sampling occurring at a level designed
to disclose, with 95% confidence, a national rate of infection of 0.02% or
higher. Within the Okanagan Valley itself, at 5 sites of highest historic
sero-prevalence, reside sentinel cattle herds.
On the basis of the above and elevated, ancillary regional serological
testing within the provinces of British Columbia and Alberta, incursions of
Bluetongue serotype 11 have been documented within the limited Okanagan
Valley focus on 4 occasions.
Age-specific prevalence rates associated with the testing of the Okanagan
Valley's entire domestic, and husbanded wild, ruminant populations in 1976
and 1977 suggested an incursion in 1972. Passive surveillance detected
clinical infection of domestic and husbanded wild ruminants in 1987.
Sentinel cattle herds, established subsequent to that outbreak, revealed
incursions in 1988 and 1998. No clinical, virological or serological
evidence of infection has been revealed except in animals from the Okanagan
Valley of British Columbia, which experience these periodic northward
extensions from the state of Washington.
Until 1998, the triennial national serological surveys employed a primary
screening regimen whose diagnostic scope included Bluetongue and Epizootic
Hemorrhagic Disease. The limited number of reactions which, by secondary
serum neutralization, were shown referable to EHD, derived almost
exclusively from cattle native to the Okanagan Valley.
For further information on Canada's status referable to these two diseases,
the reader may wish to conduct a Medline search for articles by Sellers RF
at
.
---
J.A.Kellar
Chief, Animal Disease Surveillance Unit
Canadian Food Inspection Agency
<jkellar@EM.AGR.CA>
